benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: DELETE /1.0/kb/invoicePayments/{paymentId}/tags - Remove tags from payment

covered: Valid Request: Scenarios cover successful deletion with various tagDef inputs (single/multiple, none).
Non-Existent Resource/Invalid Input Handling: Scenarios cover invalid paymentId format, non-existent paymentId, missing header, invalid tagDef values, tagDef not present on payment.
Authorization/Headers: Scenario covers missing required header (401) and valid header usage; includes header-driven actions.
Edge Cases and Behavior: Scenarios for delete with no tags, extra query parameters, injection attempt, and system unavailable scenarios covered (503).
Data Integrity/Post-Conditions: Scenarios assert tags removal affects subsequent GET results and audit/log considerations in applicable tests.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination handling for large datasets when listing or confirming tag removals.
Caching Behavior: No tests verify caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or cache invalidation after deletions.
Rate Limiting/Throttling: No tests simulate rapid consecutive DELETE requests or rate-limiting behavior.
Backward Compatibility beyond status (e.g., 204 with older clients) beyond TC19: only basic 204 expectations; more explicit compatibility checks could help.
Soft Deletes/Consequence Tracing: Explicit soft-delete semantics or audit trail checks beyond general logging are not deeply tested across all scenarios.
recommendations: Add pagination-focused tests for listing or confirming large numbers of tags to ensure pagination behaves correctly and does not drop data.
Add tests validating caching behavior, including ETag handling and Cache-Control headers, and cache invalidation after deletions.
Introduce rate-limiting and concurrency stress tests to explicitly verify behavior under high request volume and ensure graceful degradation.
Extend backward compatibility tests to cover varying client versions with explicit expectations beyond 204 status, including header semantics and data visibility.
Incorporate more explicit audit/log verification across scenarios (e.g., TC20) to ensure all required fields are captured consistently.
